-- Japan, India, Malaysia, South Korea, Taiwan: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-10-07T21:33:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-07/japan-south-korea-malaysia-taiwan-india-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Bank of Japan will publish at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo the
minutes of its Sept. 6-7 policy board meeting.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on the current-account balance for August. Japan’s
current-account surplus narrowed to 1.02 trillion yen ($12.3
billion) in August from 1.68 trillion yen in July, according to
a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on confidence among Japanese merchants in September. The
Economy Watchers Index, a survey of barbers, taxi drivers and
others who deal with consumers, fell to 44.5 in September from
45.1 in August, a separate Bloomberg survey showed.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.88 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 82.35 per dollar at 6:25 a.m. in Tokyo.  India: The government plans to raise 110 billion rupees
($2.5 billion) selling bonds maturing in 2017, 2022 and 2040 at
an auction today, according to the finance ministry.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.95
percent. The rupee was at 44.195.  Malaysia: The Department of Statistics is expected to say
exports grew 13.7 percent in August compared to a year ago,
after gaining 13.5 percent in July, according to a median
estimate in a Bloomberg survey. Imports rose 22.9 percent after
gaining 18.1 percent in July, according to the same survey.  The government is scheduled to auction more existing notes
due September 2017 this month, according to its sale calendar.
It may disclose the amount and date of the offering as early as
today. It first sold the securities on July 29 to yield 3.73
percent.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.25 percent. The ringgit was at 3.092 per dollar.  South Korea: The Bank of Korea will release producer prices
for September. Prices rose 3.1 percent in August, the slowest
pace in five months.  The yield on the 3.75 percent security due June 2013 was
3.3 percent. The won traded at 1,121.90 per dollar.  Taiwan: Taiwan’s central bank will auction NT$100 billion
($3.3 billion) of 364-day certificates of deposit.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due September 2020 was
1.18 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$31.042 per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will announce foreign-
exchange reserves for the week ended Oct. 1 today. Reserves rose
2.5 percent to $163.1 billion the previous week, according to
central bank data.  The central bank will sell 75 billion baht ($2.5 billion)
of 15-day bills and 20 billion baht of 2013 floating-rate notes.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 2.98
percent. The baht was at 29.96.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at   fyoon2@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
